Here is a comprehensive, exam-ready breakdown of **Unit 1.2 — Structure and Composition of Atmosphere, Hydrosphere, Lithosphere, and Biosphere**, covering every angle UGC NET might test.

---

## The Four Spheres of Earth

The Earth system is divided into four major spheres that interact continuously. Let's go through each one with the depth and precision needed to handle any question format.

---

### 🌫️ Atmosphere

The atmosphere is the gaseous envelope surrounding Earth, held by gravity, extending up to ~10,000 km but with 99% of its mass within 30 km.

**Composition of the Dry Atmosphere:**

| Gas | % by Volume |
|---|---|
| Nitrogen (N₂) | 78.09% |
| Oxygen (O₂) | 20.95% |
| Argon (Ar) | 0.93% |
| Carbon dioxide (CO₂) | ~0.04% (variable) |
| Other gases (Ne, He, CH₄, Kr, H₂, N₂O, O₃) | Trace |

> **Tricky exam point**: Water vapour (H₂O) is NOT included in dry composition — it is variable (0–4%). Ozone is a trace gas but critically important. CO₂ is a variable gas (not constant), unlike N₂ and O₂.

**Layers of the Atmosphere** (bottom to top):**Critical temperature gradient pattern** (most frequently tested):
- Troposphere: temperature **decreases** with altitude (normal lapse rate ~6.5°C/km)
- Stratosphere: temperature **increases** (due to ozone absorbing UV)
- Mesosphere: temperature **decreases** again
- Thermosphere: temperature **increases** sharply

> This alternating pattern is a favourite MCQ trap — remember **DIDI** (Down, Increase, Down, Increase).

