### 💧 Hydrosphere

The hydrosphere includes all water on, above, and within Earth's surface.

**Distribution of Water on Earth:**

| Reservoir | % of Total Water |
|---|---|
| Oceans | ~96.5% |
| Ice caps / glaciers | ~1.74% |
| Groundwater | ~1.69% |
| Surface freshwater (lakes, rivers, swamps) | ~0.013% |
| Soil moisture, atmosphere, biota | Tiny fractions |

> **Tricky point**: ~97.5% of all water is saline; only ~2.5% is fresh. Of freshwater, ~69% is locked in glaciers — so liquid freshwater available to ecosystems is extremely small.

**Key properties of water relevant to environment:**
- Highest specific heat capacity among common substances → regulates climate
- Universal solvent → carries dissolved salts, minerals, gases
- Anomalous expansion at 4°C (maximum density) → ice floats, protecting aquatic life in winter
- High latent heat of vaporisation → important in heat transfer across atmosphere

**Zones of the ocean** (tested frequently):
- Photic zone: 0–200 m (sunlight penetrates, photosynthesis occurs)
- Aphotic zone: below 200 m (no light)
- Abyssal zone: 4000–6000 m
- Hadal zone: >6000 m (ocean trenches)

