### 🪨 Lithosphere

The lithosphere is the solid outer shell of Earth, comprising the **crust + upper mantle**, extending to ~100 km depth.

**Internal structure of Earth:**

| Layer | Depth | Composition |
|---|---|---|
| Continental crust | 30–70 km thick | Sialic (Si + Al) — granite type |
| Oceanic crust | 5–10 km thick | Simatic (Si + Mg) — basaltic type |
| Mantle | 35–2900 km | Peridotite (Si, Mg, Fe) — plastic/viscous |
| Outer core | 2900–5100 km | Liquid Fe + Ni — generates magnetic field |
| Inner core | 5100–6371 km | Solid Fe + Ni |

> **Tricky distinction**: The **lithosphere** ≠ **crust**. Lithosphere = crust + rigid upper mantle. The **asthenosphere** (below lithosphere, ~100–350 km) is partially molten and allows tectonic plate movement.

**SIAL vs SIMA** (exam favourite):
- SIAL = Continental crust (Silicon + Aluminium), lighter, density ~2.7 g/cm³
- SIMA = Oceanic crust (Silicon + Magnesium), heavier, density ~3.0 g/cm³

**Mohorovičić Discontinuity (Moho):** Boundary between crust and mantle — marked by sharp increase in seismic wave velocity.

**Gutenberg Discontinuity:** Boundary between mantle and outer core (~2900 km).

**Lehmann Discontinuity:** Boundary between outer and inner core (~5100 km).

