### 🌿 Biosphere

The biosphere is the zone of life — the global sum of all ecosystems, extending from ~11 km below ocean surface to ~10 km altitude in atmosphere (wherever life exists).

**Boundaries of the biosphere:**
- Extends across parts of all three other spheres
- Lower limit: ~11 km (deep ocean trenches — chemolithotrophs)
- Upper limit: ~10 km altitude (some microorganisms, spores in atmosphere)
- Thermophiles in deep-sea hydrothermal vents: up to 121°C

**Key concepts:**
- **Biosphere ≠ ecosphere**: Some use these interchangeably, but technically ecosphere includes the physical environment interacting with biota.
- The biosphere is entirely dependent on energy from the sun (and chemosynthesis in a few exceptional ecosystems).
- It acts as the interface where matter cycles (C, N, P, S, H₂O) between lithosphere, hydrosphere, and atmosphere.

---

### Interactions Between the Four Spheres

This is where many higher-order UGC NET questions come from. Every environmental process involves sphere interactions:

| Process | Spheres Involved |
|---|---|
| Photosynthesis | Biosphere + Atmosphere + Hydrosphere |
| Weathering of rocks | Lithosphere + Hydrosphere + Atmosphere |
| Acid rain | Atmosphere + Hydrosphere + Lithosphere + Biosphere |
| Carbon cycle | All four spheres |
| Soil formation (pedogenesis) | Lithosphere + Biosphere + Hydrosphere + Atmosphere |
| Volcanic eruption | Lithosphere → Atmosphere (CO₂, SO₂, ash) |
| El Niño | Hydrosphere ↔ Atmosphere |

